    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It's good to read that a handful of state attorneys general recognize global warming as a public nuisance (''A Novel Tactic on Warming,'' editorial, July 28).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It's good to read that a handful of state attorneys general recognize global warming as a public nuisance (''A Novel Tactic on Warming,'' editorial, July 28).</p>
        <p>I reside in the semi-arid West, where scientists are just beginning to understand the enormous synergistic impact of global warming, atmospheric drying (drought) and the explosion in insect populations that's killing many of our forests. When one lives in the shadow of one of these dead or dying forests, public nuisance is an understatement -- it's close to total devastation.</p>
        <p>On a recent vacation in the Northwest, I drove through Sun Valley, Idaho. Around Sun Valley and the nearby Salmon River Valley, entire mountainsides of forest are now being destroyed by out-of-control bark beetle infestations. Could the attorneys general convince the judge that insects love the warmer weather caused by global warming? Dead forests are a public nuisance extraordinaire, and we tragically have mountains of evidence all around us.</p>
        <p>Bill McEwen  Yucaipa, Calif., July 29, 2004</p>
      </block>
